Raul, Alfonso, Carlos, Jaime, Jesus, Miguel, Alberto, Blanca.","Spanish (Burgos and Biscay): nickname from <i>granillo</i>, a diminutive of <i>grano</i> ‘grain’ (see   Grano  ), probably in the sense ‘pimple’. This surname is most common in Mexico.","Italian (Campania): diminutive of   Grano   ‘grain’."]},{"name":"Granese","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Lucio, Rocco, Salvatore.","Italian (Campania): derivative of   Grano  ."]}]},{"name":"Vachan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Czech Alois, Zdenka.","Czech (<b>Macháň</b>) and Slovak (also <b>Machán</b>): from a derivative of the personal name   Mach  .","English (Yorkshire): variant of   Machen  . It is also found in Lanarkshire, Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Mach","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Huy, Minh, To, Hoa, Hung, Muoi, Quang, Tan, Anh, Binh, Chau, Chuc.","Czech, Slovak, Polish, Ukrainian, and Sorbian: from the personal name <i>Mach</i>, a pet form of names beginning with <i>Ma-</i>, e.g. <i>Matěj</i> in Czech (see   Matej  ),   Martin   in Slovak, and   Maciej   in Polish.","Possibly also an Americanized form of Hungarian <b>Mács</b>: from a pet form of <i>Máté</i> or <i>Mátyás</i>, Hungarian forms of the personal name   Matthew  ."]}]},{"name":"Howell","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the Welsh name Hywel , or a transferred use of the surname derived from that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Hywel","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname from a vocabulary word meaning ‘eminent, conspicuous’; it was common in the Middle Ages and was revived in the 20th-century."]}]},{"name":"Ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Howell Ap Grono Vachan was born in 1380, in Wales, his father, Grono Ap Ivor Hir Vachan, was 38 and his mother, Catherina Ap Jenki